Two of the main forms of financial crime are:
=09You have a business that does not make any money, but you=E2=80=99d like=
 people to=C2=A0think=C2=A0that it makes money, so that they will give you =
money. So you write financial statements that say you have a lot of income,=
 but you don=E2=80=99t; the money that you are earning is fake.=C2=A0=09You=
 have a business that makes a lot of money, but by doing crime. You would l=
ike to be able to spend the money in the legitimate financial system, use i=
t to buy houses or sports teams or Treasury bills or whatever. So you write=
 financial statements that say you have a lot of income from legitimate act=
ivity, but you don=E2=80=99t; your income statements =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the=
 legitimate activities they describe =E2=80=94=C2=A0are fake.=C2=A0But the =
money is real.=C2=A0

One risk for short sellers or journalists or other sorts of investigators l=
ooking into a financial fraud is mistaking=C2=A0Thing 2, money laundering, =
for Thing 1, regular financial fraud. Thing 1 is more tractable, to the ave=
rage sort of financial person. Thing 1 is a crime of spreadsheets: The crim=
inal act consists of writing a spreadsheet with fake numbers in it and gett=
ing your auditors to believe it.=C2=A0Thing 2 is a crime of, you know, crim=
e; the people doing that crime have=C2=A0also=C2=A0done the underlying crim=
e that they are concealing, or at least they work for people who did it. Of=
ten that underlying crime took place in physical reality rather than spread=
sheets, and the people who do it are scarier=C2=A0than people who mainly ma=
nipulate spreadsheets.
  [1]

The risk, for an investigator, is that you find a company with fake account=
s and say =E2=80=9Caha this company has fake accounts, it didn=E2=80=99t re=
ally make all this money, the money isn=E2=80=99t there, I will expose this=
 person who is typing lies in a spreadsheet!=E2=80=9D And then you find out=
 that in fact the money=C2=A0is=C2=A0there, but it belongs to Russian merce=
naries who did not want to be exposed, whoops!
At the New Yorker, Ben Taub has an  absolutely rollicking story about the c=
ollapse of Wirecard, the fraudulent German payments company that was expose=
d by Dan McCrum at the Financial Times. Oversimplifying it a bit, the main =
thing that McCrum found is that Wirecard kept partnering with local busines=
ses in Asia that turned out to be fake; ultimately, in 2020, it =E2=80=9Can=
nounced that nearly two billion euros was missing from the company=E2=80=99=
s accounts,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Camounted to all the profits that Wireca=
rd had ever reported as a public company.=E2=80=9D There are competing, par=
tially overlapping theories about how that happened. Here is the traditiona=
l one:
Over coffee in London, a hedge-fund manager named Leo Perry shared with McC=
rum his theory: Wirecard=E2=80=99s primary business model was to lie to the=
 public, claiming huge profits, so that investors would push up its share p=
rice. However, =E2=80=9Cfaking profits, you end up with a problem of fake c=
ash,=E2=80=9D Perry said. =E2=80=9CAt the end of the year, the auditor will=
 expect to see a healthy bank balance=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s the first thing =
they check. So what you have to do is spend that fake cash on fake assets=
=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94dormant shell companies in Asia, reported as profitable i=
nvestments.
Report fake profits, generate fake income, use the fake income to buy more =
fake companies that generate more fake profits: straightforward stuff, fina=
ncial fraud, a spreadsheet crime. Here is the other theory:

[Short seller Fahmi] Quadir and [her employee Christina]=C2=A0Clementi cult=
ivated confidential sources in the payments industry, and developed a worki=
ng theory: that the company=E2=80=99s primary business purpose was to serve=
 organized criminal networks and Russian oligarchs=E2=80=94to be a =E2=80=
=9Cone-stop-shop=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Clarge-scale money laundering operati=
ons that would require scale to support billions in dirty money, annually,=
=E2=80=9D they wrote, in a presentation for Safkhet investors. The key was =
Wirecard=E2=80=99s banking license, which enabled it both to accept crimina=
l funds and to obscure their source. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CYou cannot understand Wirecard if you understand Wirecard only as =
fraud,=E2=80=9D Felix Holtermann, a financial reporter at Handelsblatt, tol=
d me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not a Potemkin village, it=E2=80=99s not a Bern=
ie Madoff case.=E2=80=9D According to Holtermann, who has also written a bo=
ok about the company, Marsalek routinely =E2=80=9Cused his power to overrid=
e Wirecard=E2=80=99s very, very small compliance department=E2=80=9D to iss=
ue bank accounts, credit cards, and debit cards to Russian oligarchs who we=
re on European financial blacklists. =E2=80=9CGermany was, and still is, th=
e money-laundering saloon of Europe,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9COnly the bi=
ggest washing machine broke.=E2=80=9D

Quadir was eventually =E2=80=9Cpunched in the head by a masked man with bra=
ss knuckles while walking her poodle on the Upper West Side,=E2=80=9D thoug=
h it is unclear whether that is related to Wirecard. But=C2=A0Jan Marsalek,=
 the chief operating officer of Wirecard, uh =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chelped=
 facilitate a deployment of Russian mercenaries into Libya,=E2=80=9D is one=
 thing he did? Or there=E2=80=99s this meeting with Paul Murphy, McCrum=E2=
=80=99s editor at the FT:
That fall, Marsalek summoned Murphy to Germany for another lunch, in a priv=
ate dining room, and handed him a stack of documents. They contained offici=
al Russian government talking points, addressed to the U.N.=E2=80=99s chemi=
cal-weapons body, casting doubt on the British investigation of the Skripal=
 poisoning. The files=E2=80=94marked classified=E2=80=94also contained the =
chemical formula for Novichok. =E2=80=9CWhere did you get these?=E2=80=9D M=
urphy asked. Marsalek smiled and said, =E2=80=9CFriends.=E2=80=9D
Ah! Or:

By now, Marsalek had fully entrenched himself in the affairs of his Russian=
 mercenary friend, Stanislav Petlinsky. Wirecard arranged a deal with the R=
.S.B. Group=E2=80=99s holding company in Dubai, to sell the mercenaries its=
 prepaid-debit-card software. In an encrypted chat with Dagmar Schneider, a=
 senior member of Wirecard=E2=80=99s finance team, Marsalek wrote that if a=
uditors had questions about R.S.B. they should call Vladimir Putin. As McCr=
um and Palma closed in on the fraud in the Philippines, Marsalek joked with=
 Schneider about having people =E2=80=9Cshot by MY Russians at RSB.=E2=80=
=9D The following week, he wrote to her that he had =E2=80=9Cbeen strugglin=
g with the FT since 5 in the morning.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CSend YOUR Russians to London,=E2=80=9D Schneider replied. =E2=80=
=9CThey should give us some peace.=E2=80=9D

See if someone came to me and said=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthere is a company that fo=
ols its auditors using dormant shell companies,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99d be lik=
e, ooh, fun, financial shenanigans. But if they said =E2=80=9Cand its leade=
r has fully entrenched himself in the affairs of his Russian mercenary frie=
nd,=E2=80=9D I would be worried.

