   =20
      Biochar
   =20
 =20

A  standard thesis of environmental, social and governance (but especially =
environmental) investing is that companies regularly do stuff that causes e=
xternalities, and over time laws and norms will evolve so that they will ha=
ve to  internalize those externalities. One way for that thesis to work is =
something like this:
=09There is some company that makes some product that it sells for a lot of=
 money, but the production process creates a lot of pollution.=09Right now,=
 that pollution is =E2=80=9Cfree=E2=80=9D: The company can dump its poisono=
us byproducts in the nearest river or whatever. This makes the production p=
rocess cheap, so the company is profitable.=09But soon, the pollution proba=
bly won=E2=80=99t be free: The local government will probably tell the comp=
any not to dump its byproducts, or else customers will refuse=C2=A0to buy t=
he product because they are more attuned to environmental issues and don=E2=
=80=99t want to encourage pollution.=09So the company will have to clean up=
 its process, which will be expensive, making the company less profitable o=
r perhaps not viable at all.=09As an investor, you should think about the l=
ikely future restrictions on pollution, and avoid buying companies that are=
 profitable now only because they impose externalities on the world that ar=
e not properly priced.

This sort of story makes sense, though you can=C2=A0quibble with specific c=
ases. (Sometimes ESG thinking  relies on assumptions about future regulatio=
n that are at odds with, you know, the actual regulators.)
Symmetry suggests that there might be companies that produce positive=C2=A0=
externalities, and over time laws and norms will evolve so that they will g=
et to internalize those externalities:=C2=A0
=09There is some company that makes some product that it sells for some bar=
ely viable amount of money, but the production process somehow cleans up ne=
arby rivers.=09Right now, nobody is paying the company for cleaning up the =
rivers.=09But soon, somebody probably will: Whoever wants=C2=A0rivers to be=
 clean will start writing the company a check for its good behavior.=09So t=
he company will be much more profitable and can expand its production.

Here is a fun Wall Street Journal story about biochar:

Biochar is a black substance similar to charcoal that when buried undergrou=
nd sequesters carbon dioxide, the primary greenhouse gas that causes climat=
e change. It has long been used to improve soil. Now it has suddenly become=
 a lucrative business thanks to carbon credits that companies use to offset=
 their own emissions. =E2=80=A6
Among the buyers are JPMorgan Chase and Microsoft Corp. They are attracted =
to a process that actually removes carbon from the atmosphere and buries it=
 underground, rather than many credits whose impact on emissions isn=E2=80=
=99t clear. ...
There isn=E2=80=99t much money to be made selling biochar to improve soil. =
Carbon credits changed that. =E2=80=9CWhen the only potential revenue was t=
hrough biochar sales, there just really wasn=E2=80=99t much there,=E2=80=9D=
 said Josiah Hunt, chief executive of Pacific Biochar Benefit Corp., a Cali=
fornia startup that works with biomass power plants to produce biochar, the=
n sells it to farmers.=C2=A0
Carbon-credit sales now generate millions of dollars for some biochar busin=
esses. =E2=80=9CThe carbon credits and society=E2=80=99s decision to act on=
 climate change make this a real business,=E2=80=9D Mr. Hunt said.
He was working as a landscaper in 2008 when he read an article in National =
Geographic about biochar=E2=80=99s potential to boost soil health and addre=
ss climate change. After making his own biochar and testing it in soils, he=
 launched the company that became Pacific Biochar a few years later.
The business struggled because the price was too high, roughly $600 a ton. =
That changed in late 2020 when the company started selling carbon credits f=
or roughly $150 per ton of carbon dioxide removed to Microsoft and others t=
hrough a platform called Carbonfuture.
The extra revenue let Mr. Hunt cut prices and sales grew. He now delivers b=
iochar to vineyards and other businesses. Pacific Biochar=E2=80=99s sales a=
re expected to hit a few million dollars this year, the majority of which i=
s money from carbon credits.=C2=A0

The point here is that this is a real normal business =E2=80=94=C2=A0produc=
ers produce biochar and sell it to farmers who want better soil =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but it is a barely viable business, because the cost of producing the=
 biochar is higher than most farmers are willing to pay. But it produces po=
sitive externalities, and if you can get someone to pay you for those then =
you=E2=80=99ve got a viable business.
How do you get people to pay you for those externalities? In theory everyon=
e on earth benefits from having less carbon in the atmosphere; I guess you =
could take up a collection. But in practice the answer is that some compani=
es create negative externalities in the form of carbon emissions, and due t=
o some combination of regulation, customer pressure, shareholder pressure, =
employee pressure, etc., they have to internalize those externalities. And =
instead of doing that themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0by not producing stuff that=
 creates carbon emissions, by telling their employees not to get on planes =
to visit clients, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0they buy carbon credits in a fina=
ncial marketplace. They internalize the bad externalities by buying good ex=
ternalities from the biochar people.
Elsewhere in ESG, here is a Wall Street Journal story about anti-ESG that i=
ncludes the sentences =E2=80=9CConservative activists are coordinating a mu=
ltimillion-dollar national campaign to make ESG the next CRT=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9CA digital ad by the Heritage Foundation=E2=80=99s political-action=
 committee portrays an oil-and-gas driller being denied a small-business lo=
an in part because he has never =E2=80=98identified as a woman or even nonb=
inary.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D

