   =20
      Wormhole=C2=A0
   =20
 =20

In general, in the US, most people have the mostly correct sense that if so=
meone scams some money out of their bank account, they can call their bank =
and the bank will put it back. The intuitive process is roughly:
=09Someone scams you into sending them money from your bank account.=09You =
call your bank and say =E2=80=9CI was scammed, my transfer of $2,000 last T=
hursday was a fraud,=E2=80=9D and provide some details.=09Your bank looks a=
t where the money was sent and calls=C2=A0the recipient=C2=A0bank =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the scammer=E2=80=99s bank =E2=80=94 to say that the transaction was =
a fraud.=09The recipient bank takes the money out of the scammer=E2=80=99s =
account and sends it back to your bank, which puts it back in your account.

This is not a completely accurate description of the process or anything, a=
nd there are various imperfections; in particular, knowing this risk, the s=
cammer might sensibly move the money=C2=A0out=C2=A0of the recipient account=
 as soon as she gets it. She might move it among a bunch of banks to obscur=
e its provenance, or she might move it to a bank in a less regulated jurisd=
iction to avoid having to give it back, or she might take it out of the ban=
k in $100 bills before you notice that you were scammed.
  [2]
=C2=A0But broadly speaking bank transactions are reversible: Banks are regu=
lated entities that keep lists of who has money, and if the lists get messe=
d up due to fraud or hacking then people at the banks will try to fix them.
In crypto, things are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know =E2=80=A6. differ=
ent-ish? A little different? Philosophically, crypto has an ethos of   irre=
versible transactions and immutable code; when crypto platforms are hacked =
the hackers will  sometimes boast that they were just doing what the code a=
llowed them to do.=C2=A0But practically:
=09Crypto transactions are=C2=A0really=C2=A0traceable, in many ways easier =
to trace than transactions in the regular banking system: Blockchain transa=
ctions are public and immutable, and removing crypto from the system by tur=
ning it into $100 bills or real estate or bank deposits is often challengin=
g.=C2=A0=09The code mostly isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0that=C2=A0immutable: In some=
=C2=A0bits of crypto,=C2=A0somebody probably has the ability to block or fr=
eeze transactions, to modify smart contracts, or even to send crypto from o=
ne address to another without the permission of the person holding it. This=
 isn=E2=80=99t true of=C2=A0every=C2=A0bit of crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=
=80=99s not true of the Bitcoin blockchain, say =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you just=
 need to find the right bit.=09In practice the people who have the ability =
to block or freeze or reverse transactions might be susceptible to the same=
 sorts of appeals as a banker would be. =E2=80=9CWe were defrauded and that=
=E2=80=99s unfair, look at the evidence=E2=80=9D might work. Or: =E2=80=9CL=
ook at this court order we got.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t =
stop this fraud you will be a criminal accessory to money laundering.=E2=80=
=9D Those sorts of appeals.

Anyway last year a crypto bridge called Wormhole   was hacked, and about $3=
20 million was stolen; Jump Crypto, a large crypto trading firm, ended up e=
ating most of the loss. Because it is crypto, people =E2=80=94=C2=A0includi=
ng Jump =E2=80=94=C2=A0were able to track where the money went. Pleasingly =
it went into crypto gambling;  Molly White writes:
Rather than trying to launder and then cash out their profits into fiat, th=
ey have instead moved the funds through various decentralized finance (defi=
) protocols. In late January 2023, after a period of dormancy, they began t=
o take highly-leveraged positions on the liquid Ethereum staking derivative=
s stETH (Lido) and rETH (RocketPool). In fact, between the capital they dep=
loyed and the leverage, they became the third-largest holder of wrapped stE=
TH in existence. Some in the crypto industry were a little mystified, and w=
ondered if perhaps the attacker was a crypto-native taking =E2=80=9Cdegen=
=E2=80=9D positions.
But to get that leverage, the hacker went to =E2=80=94=C2=A0not a bank, but=
 to a lending protocol called Oasis. The hacker deposited its crypto in=C2=
=A0smart contracts on Oasis, but those smart contracts=E2=80=99 code was no=
t quite immutable. White:
The smart contracts for Oasis=E2=80=99s automation tools are what=E2=80=99s=
 known as upgradable smart contracts, meaning they employ a technique to ma=
ke typically immutable blockchain code mutable. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Upgradeable =
smart contracts are sometimes controlled by a single entity, but are often =
managed by a group of some kind, such as a DAO or a multi-signature contrac=
t (multisig). =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Oasis used a multisig. If Oasis wanted to upgr=
ade a contract, four of its twelve multisig members needed to approve the d=
ecision. =E2=80=A6 Because Oasis is controlled by a company, Oazo, the key =
holders are likely just a group of Oazo employees. ...
You can probably figure out where this is going. Jump apparently went to Oa=
sis and said =E2=80=9Cyou have money that belongs to us.=E2=80=9D They also=
 got a court order to get it back. Oasis obligingly modified the smart cont=
racts to give the crypto back to Jump, and Jump took it:
Once the funds were under Jump=E2=80=99s control, they exited the positions=
 in the Oasis vaults, repaid the $78 million loan that the hacker had taken=
 out from Oasis, and returned the 120,695 wstETH (currently ~$214 million) =
and 3,214 rETH (~$5.5 million) to their own pockets for a total recovery of=
 a bit more than $140 million at today=E2=80=99s prices. Although ETH price=
s in USD have come down considerably from the initial hack, those staking d=
erivatives could be exchanged for approximately 137,537 ETH, meaning Jump a=
ctually came out of this whole debacle with 17,500 ETH more than the 120,00=
0 that was stolen a year ago.
Blockworks, which first reported this story, used the headline =E2=80=9CJum=
p Crypto Just Counter-Exploited the Wormhole Hacker for $140 Million.=E2=80=
=9D Did they? I suppose that in crypto, philosophically, if you got hacked,=
 and you manage to get the money back, you would prefer for the story to be=
 =E2=80=9CJump Crypto cleverly hacked the hacker using hacking tools, becau=
se crypto is trustless and decentralized and sometimes you have to hack hac=
kers,=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9CJump Crypto called customer service and=
 had the transaction reversed.=E2=80=9D

