10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Wirecard!</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two of the main forms of financial crime are:<=
/p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have a business that does not mak=
e any money, but you=E2=80=99d like people to=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>that=
 it makes money, so that they will give you money. So you write financial s=
tatements that say you have a lot of income, but you don=E2=80=99t; the mon=
ey that you are earning is fake.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">You have a business that makes a lot of money, but by doing crime. You=
 would like to be able to spend the money in the legitimate financial syste=
m, use it to buy houses or sports teams or Treasury bills or whatever. So y=
ou write financial statements that say you have a lot of income from legiti=
mate activity, but you don=E2=80=99t; your income statements =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0and the legitimate activities they describe =E2=80=94=C2=A0are fake.=C2=
=A0But the money is real.=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One risk for short sellers or journalists or o=
ther sorts of investigators looking into a financial fraud is mistaking=C2=
=A0Thing 2, money laundering, for Thing 1, regular financial fraud. Thing 1=
 is more tractable, to the average sort of financial person. Thing 1 is a c=
rime of spreadsheets: The criminal act consists of writing a spreadsheet wi=
th fake numbers in it and getting your auditors to believe it.=C2=A0Thing 2=
 is a crime of, you know, crime; the people doing that crime have=C2=A0<em>=
also=C2=A0</em>done the underlying crime that they are concealing, or at le=
ast they work for people who did it. Often that underlying crime took place=
 in physical reality rather than spreadsheets, and the people who do it are=
 <em>scarier=C2=A0</em>than people who mainly manipulate spreadsheets.<a cl=
ass=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparen=
t !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The risk, for an investigator, is that you fin=
d a company with fake accounts and say =E2=80=9Caha this company has fake a=
ccounts, it didn=E2=80=99t really make all this money, the money isn=E2=80=
=99t there, I will expose this person who is typing lies in a spreadsheet!=
=E2=80=9D And then you find out that in fact the money=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</e=
m>there, but it belongs to Russian mercenaries who did not want to be expos=
ed, whoops!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the New Yorker, Ben Taub has an <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cubmV3eW9ya2VyLmNvbS9tYWdhemluZS8yMDIzLzAzLzA2L2hvdy10aGUtYmlnZ2VzdC1mcmF1=
ZC1pbi1nZXJtYW4taGlzdG9yeS11bnJhdmVsbGVk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB88d704fc"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> absolutely rollicking story about the collapse of Wirecard</a>, t=
he fraudulent German payments company that was exposed by Dan McCrum at the=
 Financial Times. Oversimplifying it a bit, the main thing that McCrum foun=
d is that Wirecard kept partnering with local businesses in Asia that turne=
d out to be fake; ultimately, in 2020, it =E2=80=9Cannounced that nearly tw=
o billion euros was missing from the company=E2=80=99s accounts,=E2=80=9D w=
hich =E2=80=9Camounted to all the profits that Wirecard had ever reported a=
s a public company.=E2=80=9D There are competing, partially overlapping the=
ories about how that happened. Here is the traditional one:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over coffee in London, a hedge-fun=
d manager named Leo Perry shared with McCrum his theory: Wirecard=E2=80=99s=
 primary business model was to lie to the public, claiming huge profits, so=
 that investors would push up its share price. However, =E2=80=9Cfaking pro=
fits, you end up with a problem of fake cash,=E2=80=9D Perry said. =E2=80=
=9CAt the end of the year, the auditor will expect to see a healthy bank ba=
lance=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s the first thing they check. So what you have to =
do is spend that fake cash on fake assets=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94dormant shell co=
mpanies in Asia, reported as profitable investments.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Report fake profits, generate fake income, use=
 the fake income to buy more fake companies that generate more fake profits=
: straightforward stuff, financial fraud, a spreadsheet crime. Here is the =
other theory:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Short seller Fahmi] Quadir and [her employee =
Christina]=C2=A0Clementi cultivated confidential sources in the payments in=
dustry, and developed a working theory: that the company=E2=80=99s primary =
business purpose was to serve organized criminal networks and Russian oliga=
rchs=E2=80=94to be a =E2=80=9Cone-stop-shop=E2=80=9D for =E2=80=9Clarge-sca=
le money laundering operations that would require scale to support billions=
 in dirty money, annually,=E2=80=9D they wrote, in a presentation for Safkh=
et investors. The key was Wirecard=E2=80=99s banking license, which enabled=
 it both to accept criminal funds and to obscure their source. =E2=80=A6</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou cannot understand Wirecard if you=
 understand Wirecard only as fraud,=E2=80=9D Felix Holtermann, a financial =
reporter at Handelsblatt, told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not a Potemkin vil=
lage, it=E2=80=99s not a Bernie Madoff case.=E2=80=9D According to Holterma=
nn, who has also written a book about the company, Marsalek routinely =E2=
=80=9Cused his power to override Wirecard=E2=80=99s very, very small compli=
ance department=E2=80=9D to issue bank accounts, credit cards, and debit ca=
rds to Russian oligarchs who were on European financial blacklists. =E2=80=
=9CGermany was, and still is, the money-laundering saloon of Europe,=E2=80=
=9D he said. =E2=80=9COnly the biggest washing machine broke.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Quadir was eventually =E2=80=9Cpunched in the =
head by a masked man with brass knuckles while walking her poodle on the Up=
per West Side,=E2=80=9D though it is unclear whether that is related to Wir=
ecard. But=C2=A0Jan Marsalek, the chief operating officer of Wirecard, uh =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Chelped facilitate a deployment of Russian mercenari=
es into Libya,=E2=80=9D is one thing he did? Or there=E2=80=99s this meetin=
g with Paul Murphy, McCrum=E2=80=99s editor at the FT:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That fall, Marsalek summoned Murph=
y to Germany for another lunch, in a private dining room, and handed him a =
stack of documents. They contained official Russian government talking poin=
ts, addressed to the U.N.=E2=80=99s chemical-weapons body, casting doubt on=
 the British investigation of the Skripal poisoning. The files=E2=80=94mark=
ed classified=E2=80=94also contained the chemical formula for Novichok. =E2=
=80=9CWhere did you get these?=E2=80=9D Murphy asked. Marsalek smiled and s=
aid, =E2=80=9CFriends.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah! Or:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By now, Marsalek had fully entrenched himself =
in the affairs of his Russian mercenary friend, Stanislav Petlinsky. Wireca=
rd arranged a deal with the R.S.B. Group=E2=80=99s holding company in Dubai=
, to sell the mercenaries its prepaid-debit-card software. In an encrypted =
chat with Dagmar Schneider, a senior member of Wirecard=E2=80=99s finance t=
eam, Marsalek wrote that if auditors had questions about R.S.B. they should=
 call Vladimir Putin. As McCrum and Palma closed in on the fraud in the Phi=
lippines, Marsalek joked with Schneider about having people =E2=80=9Cshot b=
y MY Russians at RSB.=E2=80=9D The following week, he wrote to her that he =
had =E2=80=9Cbeen struggling with the FT since 5 in the morning.=E2=80=9D</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSend YOUR Russians to London,=E2=80=
=9D Schneider replied. =E2=80=9CThey should give us some peace.=E2=80=9D</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">See if someone came to me and said=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cthere is a company that fools its auditors using dormant shell companies=
,=E2=80=9D I=E2=80=99d be like, ooh, fun, financial shenanigans. But if the=
y said =E2=80=9Cand its leader has fully entrenched himself in the affairs =
of his Russian mercenary friend,=E2=80=9D I would be worried.</p>
