<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDktMTQvZG9uLXQtc3BlbmQteW91ci1saXRlY29pbnMtYXQtd2FsbWFyd=
D9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9=
bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB9bf575ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> standard thesis</a> of environmental, =
social and governance (but especially environmental) investing is that comp=
anies regularly do stuff that causes externalities, and over time laws and =
norms will evolve so that they will have to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMDQvZmFjZWJvb2std2hpc3RsZWJsb3dlci1zaG93=
cy1hLXNoaWZ0LWluLXNoYXJlaG9sZGVyLXZhbHVlcy1hd2F5LWZyb20tcHJvZml0cz9jbXBpZD1=
CQkQwMjI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldH=
RlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBf6b4cab6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> internalize those externalities</a>. One way for=
 that thesis to work is something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is some company that makes some=
 product that it sells for a lot of money, but the production process creat=
es a lot of pollution.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Right now, =
that pollution is =E2=80=9Cfree=E2=80=9D: The company can dump its poisonou=
s byproducts in the nearest river or whatever. This makes the production pr=
ocess cheap, so the company is profitable.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">But soon, the pollution probably won=E2=80=99t be free: The local =
government will probably tell the company not to dump its byproducts, or el=
se customers will refuse=C2=A0to buy the product because they are more attu=
ned to environmental issues and don=E2=80=99t want to encourage pollution.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So the company will have to clean =
up its process, which will be expensive, making the company less profitable=
 or perhaps not viable at all.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">As =
an investor, you should think about the likely future restrictions on pollu=
tion, and avoid buying companies that are profitable now only because they =
impose externalities on the world that are not properly priced.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This sort of story makes sense, though you can=
=C2=A0quibble with specific cases. (Sometimes ESG thinking <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMTAtMjUvZXh4b24taXMtaW4tdHJvd=
WJsZS1vdmVyLWNsaW1hdGUtY2hhbmdlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9t=
ZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIyNyZ1dG1fY2F=
tcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBec41944f" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> relies =
on assumptions</a> about future regulation that are at odds with, you know,=
 the actual regulators.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Symmetry suggests that there might be companie=
s that produce <em>positive=C2=A0</em>externalities, and over time laws and=
 norms will evolve so that they will get to internalize those externalities=
:=C2=A0</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is some company that makes some=
 product that it sells for some barely viable amount of money, but the prod=
uction process somehow cleans up nearby rivers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Right now, nobody is paying the company for cleaning up the r=
ivers.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But soon, somebody probably=
 will: Whoever wants=C2=A0rivers to be clean will start writing the company=
 a check for its good behavior.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So=
 the company will be much more profitable and can expand its production.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a fun <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2=
xlcy9hbmNpZW50LWZhcm1pbmctcHJhY3RpY2UtZHJhd3MtY2FzaC1mcm9tLWNhcmJvbi1jcmVka=
XRzLWE4MDNhZWUxP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBea72d4=
47" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Wall Street Journal story about biochar</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Biochar is a black substance similar to charco=
al that when buried underground sequesters carbon dioxide, the primary gree=
nhouse gas that causes climate change. It has long been used to improve soi=
l. Now it has suddenly become a lucrative business thanks to carbon credits=
 that companies use to offset their own emissions. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the buyers are JPMorgan Chase and Micros=
oft Corp. They are attracted to a process that actually removes carbon from=
 the atmosphere and buries it underground, rather than many credits whose i=
mpact on emissions isn=E2=80=99t clear. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There isn=E2=80=99t much money to be made sell=
ing biochar to improve soil. Carbon credits changed that. =E2=80=9CWhen the=
 only potential revenue was through biochar sales, there just really wasn=
=E2=80=99t much there,=E2=80=9D said Josiah Hunt, chief executive of Pacifi=
c Biochar Benefit Corp., a California startup that works with biomass power=
 plants to produce biochar, then sells it to farmers.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Carbon-credit sales now generate millions of d=
ollars for some biochar businesses. =E2=80=9CThe carbon credits and society=
=E2=80=99s decision to act on climate change make this a real business,=E2=
=80=9D Mr. Hunt said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He was working as a landscaper in 2008 when he=
 read an article in National Geographic about biochar=E2=80=99s potential t=
o boost soil health and address climate change. After making his own biocha=
r and testing it in soils, he launched the company that became Pacific Bioc=
har a few years later.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The business struggled because the price was t=
oo high, roughly $600 a ton. That changed in late 2020 when the company sta=
rted selling carbon credits for roughly $150 per ton of carbon dioxide remo=
ved to Microsoft and others through a platform called Carbonfuture.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The extra revenue let Mr. Hunt cut prices and =
sales grew. He now delivers biochar to vineyards and other businesses. Paci=
fic Biochar=E2=80=99s sales are expected to hit a few million dollars this =
year, the majority of which is money from carbon credits.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point here is that this is a real normal b=
usiness =E2=80=94=C2=A0producers produce biochar and sell it to farmers who=
 want better soil =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a barely viable business, becaus=
e the cost of producing the biochar is higher than most farmers are willing=
 to pay. But it produces positive externalities, and if you can get someone=
 to pay you for those then you=E2=80=99ve got a viable business.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How do you get people to pay you for those ext=
ernalities? In theory everyone on earth benefits from having less carbon in=
 the atmosphere; I guess you could take up a collection. But in practice th=
e answer is that some companies create negative externalities in the form o=
f carbon emissions, and due to some combination of regulation, customer pre=
ssure, shareholder pressure, employee pressure, etc., they have to internal=
ize those externalities. And instead of doing that themselves =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0by not producing stuff that creates carbon emissions, by telling their e=
mployees not to get on planes to visit clients, whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
y buy carbon credits in a financial marketplace. They internalize the bad e=
xternalities by buying good externalities from the biochar people.</p>
