<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, in the US, most people have the mo=
stly correct sense that if someone scams some money out of their bank accou=
nt, they can call their bank and the bank will put it back. The intuitive p=
rocess is roughly:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Someone scams you into sending them m=
oney from your bank account.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You c=
all your bank and say =E2=80=9CI was scammed, my transfer of $2,000 last Th=
ursday was a fraud,=E2=80=9D and provide some details.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Your bank looks at where the money was sent and calls=
=C2=A0the recipient<em>=C2=A0</em>bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0the scammer=E2=80=99s=
 bank =E2=80=94 to say that the transaction was a fraud.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The recipient bank takes the money out of the scam=
mer=E2=80=99s account and sends it back to your bank, which puts it back in=
 your account.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not a completely accurate description =
of the process or anything, and there are various imperfections; in particu=
lar, knowing this risk, the scammer might sensibly move the money=C2=A0<em>=
out=C2=A0</em>of the recipient account as soon as she gets it. She might mo=
ve it among a bunch of banks to obscure its provenance, or she might move i=
t to a bank in a less regulated jurisdiction to avoid having to give it bac=
k, or she might take it out of the bank in $100 bills before you notice tha=
t you were scammed.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But broadly speaking bank transactions are reversible: Banks are =
regulated entities that keep lists of who has money, and if the lists get m=
essed up due to fraud or hacking then people at the banks will try to fix t=
hem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In crypto, things are =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=
=80=99t know =E2=80=A6. different-ish? A little different? Philosophically,=
 crypto has an ethos of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMTYtMDYtMTcvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1jb21wYW55LXMtc21hcnQtY29udHJhY3RzLXdlcmUt=
ZHVtYj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjI3MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMjcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBffc11048" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  irreversible transactions and im=
mutable code</a>; when crypto platforms are hacked the hackers will <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9hLXRyYWRlci1zYXlzLWNvZGUtYWxsb3dlZC1oaW0tdG8t=
