r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> sometimes boast</a> that they were just doing what the code allowed t=
hem to do.=C2=A0But practically:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto transactions are=C2=A0<em>real=
ly=C2=A0</em>traceable, in many ways easier to trace than transactions in t=
he regular banking system: Blockchain transactions are public and immutable=
, and removing crypto from the system by turning it into $100 bills or real=
 estate or bank deposits is often challenging.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"ma=
rgin-bottom: 5px;">The code mostly isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>im=
mutable: In some=C2=A0bits of crypto,=C2=A0<em>somebody</em> probably has t=
he ability to block or freeze transactions, to modify smart contracts, or e=
ven to send crypto from one address to another without the permission of th=
e person holding it. This isn=E2=80=99t true of=C2=A0<em>every=C2=A0</em>bi=
t of crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s not true of the Bitcoin blockchain,=
 say =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you just need to find the right bit.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In practice the people who have the ability to b=
lock or freeze or reverse transactions might be susceptible to the same sor=
ts of appeals as a banker would be. =E2=80=9CWe were defrauded and that=E2=
=80=99s unfair, look at the evidence=E2=80=9D might work. Or: =E2=80=9CLook=
 at this court order we got.=E2=80=9D Or: =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t sto=
p this fraud you will be a criminal accessory to money laundering.=E2=80=9D=
 Those sorts of appeals.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway last year a crypto bridge called Wormho=
le <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30672977.261430=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMDMvZm=
